# Sidewalk and Refreshments — Inventory System
## MVP Feature List & Product Requirements Document (PRD)

**Business:** Sidewalk and Refreshments
**Location:** Dinagat Island
**System:** Restaurant Inventory Management (Django)
**Date:** April 19, 2026

---

# PART 1: MVP FEATURE LIST

The Minimum Viable Product focuses on core inventory operations that directly support daily restaurant operations.

---

## MVP Feature Scope

### 1. Item/Product Management
- Add, edit, and delete inventory items (food, beverages, supplies)
- Set item name, category, unit of measurement, and reorder threshold
- View full item list with current stock levels

### 2. Category Management
- Create and manage categories (e.g., Drinks, Food, Condiments, Packaging)
- Filter inventory view by category

### 3. Stock Tracking
- Record stock-in (restocking/delivery)
- Record stock-out (consumption/usage)
- View current quantity on hand per item

### 4. Low Stock Alerts
- Flag items that fall below the reorder threshold
- Display alert/warning on the dashboard

### 5. Basic Dashboard
- Summary view: total items, low-stock count, recent activity
- Quick navigation to core sections (Inventory, Menu, Customer view)

### 6. Menu Integration
- Link inventory items to menu items
- Support customer-facing menu page (`/customer/`)

### 7. User Access
- Single admin login (no multi-role for MVP)
- Protected routes — unauthenticated users cannot access admin views

---

## Out of Scope for MVP
- Supplier management
- Purchase order generation
- Multi-user roles (cashier, manager, etc.)
- Sales/POS integration
- Automated reorder requests
- Reporting and analytics
- Mobile app

---

# PART 2: PRODUCT REQUIREMENTS DOCUMENT (PRD)

---

## 1. Overview

**Product Name:** Sidewalk Inventory System
**Type:** Internal web application (Django)
**Primary User:** Restaurant owner / manager
**Goal:** Maintain accurate, real-time inventory records for Sidewalk and Refreshments to minimize stockouts and reduce waste.

---

## 2. Problem Statement

Sidewalk and Refreshments operates in Dinagat Island, where supply chain logistics can be challenging. Manual tracking of inventory leads to stockouts, over-ordering, and operational inefficiency. The system must give the owner a clear, reliable picture of stock at all times.

---

## 3. Goals & Success Metrics

| Goal | Success Metric |
|------|---------------|
| Reduce stockouts | Low-stock alerts fired before item runs out 90% of the time |
| Accurate stock count | Inventory count matches physical count within ±5% weekly |
| Ease of use | Owner can log a stock transaction in under 60 seconds |
| System reliability | Uptime ≥ 99% during business hours |

---

## 4. User Personas

**Primary — The Owner/Manager**
- Non-technical user
- Logs in daily to check inventory and record deliveries
- Needs simple, fast interface on desktop or tablet

**Secondary — Customers (read-only)**
- Views the menu page (`/customer/`)
- No account required; no inventory access

---

## 5. Functional Requirements

### 5.1 Authentication
| ID | Requirement |
|----|-------------|
| AUTH-01 | Admin user must log in with username and password |
| AUTH-02 | All inventory/dashboard routes redirect to login if unauthenticated |
| AUTH-03 | Logout clears session |

### 5.2 Item Management
| ID | Requirement |
|----|-------------|
| ITEM-01 | Admin can create an inventory item with: name, category, unit, current quantity, reorder threshold |
| ITEM-02 | Admin can edit any field of an existing item |
| ITEM-03 | Admin can delete an item (soft delete or confirmation modal) |
| ITEM-04 | Items list is paginated or searchable if count exceeds 20 |

### 5.3 Category Management
| ID | Requirement |
|----|-------------|
| CAT-01 | Admin can create, rename, and delete categories |
| CAT-02 | Inventory list can be filtered by category |
| CAT-03 | Each item belongs to exactly one category |

### 5.4 Stock Transactions
| ID | Requirement |
|----|-------------|
| TXN-01 | Admin can record a stock-in event (quantity added, date, optional note) |
| TXN-02 | Admin can record a stock-out event (quantity removed, date, optional note) |
| TXN-03 | Each transaction updates the item's current quantity in real time |
| TXN-04 | Transaction history is viewable per item |

### 5.5 Low Stock Alerts
| ID | Requirement |
|----|-------------|
| ALERT-01 | Items at or below their reorder threshold are flagged visually (e.g., red badge) |
| ALERT-02 | Dashboard displays count of low-stock items |
| ALERT-03 | Low-stock items section on dashboard lists the affected items |

### 5.6 Dashboard
| ID | Requirement |
|----|-------------|
| DASH-01 | Shows total number of inventory items |
| DASH-02 | Shows number of low-stock items |
| DASH-03 | Shows list of recent stock transactions (last 10) |
| DASH-04 | Links to inventory list, menu management, and customer view |

### 5.7 Menu & Customer View
| ID | Requirement |
|----|-------------|
| MENU-01 | Admin can manage menu items (name, description, price, category) |
| MENU-02 | Customer-facing page (`/customer/`) displays menu items |
| MENU-03 | Customer page is public (no login required) |
| MENU-04 | Menu items can optionally be linked to inventory items |

---

## 6. Non-Functional Requirements

| Category | Requirement |
|----------|-------------|
| Performance | Pages load in under 2 seconds on a standard connection |
| Security | Passwords hashed with Django's default PBKDF2; no plain-text storage |
| Usability | UI navigable without training for a non-technical owner |
| Compatibility | Works on Chrome and Firefox on desktop/tablet |
| Data Integrity | No negative stock quantities allowed |
| Backup | SQLite DB (`db.sqlite3`) backed up daily (manual or cron) |

---

## 7. Tech Stack (Existing)

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|-----------|
| Backend | Django (Python) |
| Database | SQLite (`db.sqlite3`) |
| Frontend | HTML templates (Django templating) |
| Environment | `.venv` virtual environment |
| Config | `config/settings.py` |

---

## 8. Assumptions & Constraints

- Single-user system for MVP (one admin account)
- No internet-connected POS or supplier API integrations
- Hosted locally or on a low-cost server (Dinagat Island connectivity considered)
- Django must be properly installed in the virtual environment before running (`python manage.py runserver`)

---

## 9. Risks

| Risk | Mitigation |
|------|-----------|
| Django not installed in venv (current error) | Activate venv, run `pip install django` |
| Data loss from SQLite | Implement regular file-based backups |
| Low internet reliability on island | Design for offline-capable or local network hosting |
| Owner unfamiliarity with system | Add simple onboarding instructions or tooltips |